<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2>Japanese Working Culture</h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:image {"id":5018,"linkDestination":"custom"} -->
<figure class="wp-block-image"><a href="https://pinterest.com/pin/create/bookmarklet/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fsugoii-japan.com%2Flifestyle-in-japan&amp;media=data%3Aimage%2Fsvg%2Bxml%2C%253Csvg%2520xmlns%3D%2522http%3A%2F%2Fwww.w3.org%2F2000%2Fsvg%2522%2520width%3D%25221024%2522%2520height%3D%2522683%2522%253E%253C%2Fsvg%253E&amp;description=Lifestyle%20in%20Japan%20-%20Japanese%20Working%20Culture&amp;is_video=false" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener"><img src="https://sugoii-japan.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/Lifestyle-in-Japan-Japanese-Working-Culture.jpg?ezimgfmt=rs:690x460/rscb1/ng:webp/ngcb1" alt="Lifestyle in Japan - Japanese Working Culture" class="wp-image-5018" title="Lifestyle in Japan - Japanese Working Culture"/></a></figure>
<!-- /wp:image -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>In the past, and still quite evident in companies today, those working for corporations follow an extremely strict hierarchy. There is a distinct relationship between the ‘senpai’ (experienced), and the ‘kohai’ (inexperienced).</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Most people who work in the major cities like Tokyo and Osaka typically take on office jobs and are collectively known as Japanese salarymen.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>And when you take on these jobs, there are a few assumptions that need to be made, such as: overtime is expected; you should probably not leave work before your manager does; and if your manager wants to go for a drink after work, you’ll be accompanying them.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:image {"id":5019,"linkDestination":"custom"} -->
<figure class="wp-block-image"><a href="https://pinterest.com/pin/create/bookmarklet/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fsugoii-japan.com%2Flifestyle-in-japan&amp;media=data%3Aimage%2Fsvg%2Bxml%2C%253Csvg%2520xmlns%3D%2522http%3A%2F%2Fwww.w3.org%2F2000%2Fsvg%2522%2520width%3D%25221024%2522%2520height%3D%2522666%2522%253E%253C%2Fsvg%253E&amp;description=Lifestyle%20in%20Japan%20-%20Japanese%20Working%20Culture%20Izakaya&amp;is_video=false" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener"><img src="https://sugoii-japan.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/Lifestyle-in-Japan-Japanese-Working-Culture-1.jpg?ezimgfmt=rs:690x449/rscb1/ng:webp/ngcb1" alt="Lifestyle in Japan - Japanese Working Culture Izakaya" class="wp-image-5019" title="Lifestyle in Japan - Japanese Working Culture Izakaya"/></a></figure>
<!-- /wp:image -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>In fact, it’s become somewhat of a social phenomenon for salarymen to drink themselves silly with their colleagues on a Friday night, pass out on the streets, and wake up to catch the earliest train home. You will see for yourself if you’re out and about in the city at the end of the working week!</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>These days, there are small but growing shifts in the workplace. The traditional route of spending your entire life at one company is slowly disappearing, with more and more younger people likely to become ‘furita’ and holding multiple part-time/casual jobs (for more freedom), moving overseas to work, or simply staying at home.<ins></ins></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2>Japanese Food Culture</h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:image {"id":5015,"linkDestination":"custom"} -->
<figure class="wp-block-image"><a href="https://pinterest.com/pin/create/bookmarklet/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fsugoii-japan.com%2Flifestyle-in-japan&amp;media=data%3Aimage%2Fsvg%2Bxml%2C%253Csvg%2520xmlns%3D%2522http%3A%2F%2Fwww.w3.org%2F2000%2Fsvg%2522%2520width%3D%25221024%2522%2520height%3D%2522744%2522%253E%253C%2Fsvg%253E&amp;description=Lifestyle%20in%20Japan%20-%20Noodles%20Making%20Restaurant&amp;is_video=false" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener"><img src="https://sugoii-japan.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/Lifestyle-in-Japan-Noodles-Making-Restaurant.jpg?ezimgfmt=rs:690x501/rscb1/ng:webp/ngcb1" alt="Lifestyle in Japan - Noodles Making Restaurant" class="wp-image-5015"/></a></figure>
<!-- /wp:image -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>This is probably our favourite part of lifestyle in Japan! Where do we even begin with the Japanese food culture?</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>When traveling to Japan, food is often the main focus of many itineraries. It’s so vastly different from many other countries, there are so many layers of complexities with the food culture – what to eat, how to eat it, where to eat it, etc.<ins></ins></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>First thing’s first: what people need to know is, there is so much more to Japan than sushi! Check here 10 popular Japanese dishes.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:image {"id":1353,"linkDestination":"custom"} -->
<figure class="wp-block-image"><a href="https://pinterest.com/pin/create/bookmarklet/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fsugoii-japan.com%2Flifestyle-in-japan&amp;media=data%3Aimage%2Fsvg%2Bxml%2C%253Csvg%2520xmlns%3D%2522http%3A%2F%2Fwww.w3.org%2F2000%2Fsvg%2522%2520width%3D%25221024%2522%2520height%3D%2522683%2522%253E%253C%2Fsvg%253E&amp;description=Japanese%20Dishes%20%231%20-%20Sushi&amp;is_video=false" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener"><img src="https://sugoii-japan.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/Japanese-Dishes-1-Sushi-1024x683.jpg?ezimgfmt=rs:690x460/rscb1/ng:webp/ngcb1" alt="Japanese Dishes #1 - Sushi" class="wp-image-1353" title="Japanese Dishes #1 - Sushi"/></a></figure>
<!-- /wp:image -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>One of the very first thoughts people have when thinking about Japan is how much fresh sushi they’re going to consume (we’re also putting our hands up here – guilty as charged!), and we totally get it. Sushi is delicious and easy, but did you know that some sushi establishments in Japan also consider its creation an artform?</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>There’s quite a variety of Japanese sushi rolls out there, outside of the usual maki rolls that people order. If you’re interested in finding out more, we’ve detailed an entire list of 12 traditional Japanese sushi rolls you <em>need </em>to taste here!</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:image {"id":4728,"linkDestination":"custom"} -->
<figure class="wp-block-image"><a href="https://pinterest.com/pin/create/bookmarklet/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fsugoii-japan.com%2Flifestyle-in-japan&amp;media=data%3Aimage%2Fsvg%2Bxml%2C%253Csvg%2520xmlns%3D%2522http%3A%2F%2Fwww.w3.org%2F2000%2Fsvg%2522%2520width%3D%25221024%2522%2520height%3D%2522686%2522%253E%253C%2Fsvg%253E&amp;description=Traditional%20Japanese%20Sushi%20Rolls%20-%20Eel%20Roll%20Unagi%20Maki&amp;is_video=false" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener"><img src="https://sugoii-japan.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/05/Traditional-Japanese-Sushi-Rolls-Eel-Roll-Unagi-Maki.jpg?ezimgfmt=rs:690x462/rscb1/ng:webp/ngcb1" alt="Traditional Japanese Sushi Rolls - Eel Roll Unagi Maki" class="wp-image-4728" title="Traditional Japanese Sushi Rolls - Eel Roll Unagi Maki"/></a></figure>
<!-- /wp:image -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Aside from sushi, it’s good to understand that rice is a staple in the Japanese people’s diet, and quite a few Japanese foods incorporate it. This includes donburi (which simmered or fried food is served over rice), onigiri (small parcels of rice with filling inside, wrapped in seaweed), mochi (pounded rice cakes), and the lesser-known chazuke (rice served with green tea poured in).</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:image {"id":5020,"linkDestination":"custom"} -->
<figure class="wp-block-image" id="attachment_5020"><a href="https://pinterest.com/pin/create/bookmarklet/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fsugoii-japan.com%2Flifestyle-in-japan&amp;media=data%3Aimage%2Fsvg%2Bxml%2C%253Csvg%2520xmlns%3D%2522http%3A%2F%2Fwww.w3.org%2F2000%2Fsvg%2522%2520width%3D%25221024%2522%2520height%3D%2522683%2522%253E%253C%2Fsvg%253E&amp;description=Onigiri%20%E2%80%93%20Tuna%20Mayo&amp;is_video=false" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener"><img src="https://sugoii-japan.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/Japanese-Food-Onigiri-Tuna-Mayo.jpg?ezimgfmt=rs:690x460/rscb1/ng:webp/ngcb1" alt="Japanese Food Onigiri Tuna Mayo" class="wp-image-5020"/></a><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Onigiri – Tuna Mayo</figcaption></figure>
<!-- /wp:image -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>If you’re a big fan of seafood, you’re in luck! Given Japan’s geographic location, fresh seafood is an essential to the regular Japanese diet. Whether it’s eaten live (odorigui-style, literally fresh from the ocean and sometimes still moving!), raw (sashimi), grilled (yaki), or deep-fried (tempura) – the freshness of the ocean is not too far away.&nbsp;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:image {"id":5021,"linkDestination":"custom"} -->
<figure class="wp-block-image"><a href="https://pinterest.com/pin/create/bookmarklet/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fsugoii-japan.com%2Flifestyle-in-japan&amp;media=data%3Aimage%2Fsvg%2Bxml%2C%253Csvg%2520xmlns%3D%2522http%3A%2F%2Fwww.w3.org%2F2000%2Fsvg%2522%2520width%3D%2522512%2522%2520height%3D%2522768%2522%253E%253C%2Fsvg%253E&amp;description=Japanese%20Seafood%20Shrimp&amp;is_video=false" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener"><img src="https://sugoii-japan.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/Japanese-Seafood-Shrimp.jpg?ezimgfmt=rs:512x768/rscb1/ng:webp/ngcb1" alt="Japanese Seafood Shrimp" class="wp-image-5021"/></a></figure>
<!-- /wp:image -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Go for a trip to the Toyosu market in Tokyo if you’re curious – you’ll come across many wonderful types of seafood there to ogle at!</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->
